ole in Ninglang, Yunnan, under the Reforms -- t16. The Yi Health Care System in Liangshan and Chuxiong -- tREFERENCES -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNearly seven million Yi people live in Southwest China, but most educated people outside China have never heard of them. This book, the first scholarly study in a Western language on the Yi in four decades, brings this little-known part of the world to life. Perspectives on the Yi of Southwest China is a remarkable collection of work by both Yi and foreign scholars describing their history, traditional society, and recent social changes.In addition to being valuable as an ethnographic study, this book is also an experiment in communication among three discourses: the cosmopolitan disciplines of history and the social sciences, the Chinese discourse of ethnology and ethnohistory, and the Yi folk discourse of genealogy and ritual. This book uses the case of the Yi to conduct an international conversation across formerly isolated disciplines.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aYi (Chinese people). 4aAnthropology. 4aCultural & Social. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAyi, Bamo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrne Swain, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiehl, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErzi, Ma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGa, Wu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGu, Wu, econtributor.4ctb4https://